Juniors and seniors who are interested in taking the SAT (essay included) on campus September 23rd will need to sign up in the front office during non-instructional time. We‚Äôve made it three days so far! Things have been going great, and the students have been doing so well with social distancing and sanitizing!

Our current update includes 14 students and 1 teacher in quarantine. We would again like to remind everyone of the CDC and DPH guidelines for dealing with symptoms: if anyone in your household is positive with COVID-19 or experiences symptoms of COVID-19, the entire household must quarantine.

Keep in mind that all of our students have google classroom to keep up with assignments under quarantine. Thank you all for your transparency and dedication to keeping the safety of our students and staff first this year!

We had a great first day of school! Here‚Äôs a few snapshots from the day, and stay tuned for more pics throughout the week!

Our intent is to keep our parents as informed as possible and update regularly in regards to our safety precautions. We have two students quarantined as a result of possible exposures from home. We were able to address them early this morning and appreciate our parents being transparent with us! We had a few students who had a fever this morning during temperature checks. Please remember that students must be fever-free for 48 hours before attending.

We are looking forward to day 2 and continuing to adjust to all the new changes together! See you tomorrow!

This year, many centers will have fewer seats because of social distancing guidelines and may encounter unexpected closures."

Registration for fall ACT dates will be opening by the end of this month.

Please email Mrs. Strickland when you are ready to receive your fee waiver. Keep in mind that you will be allowed only two SAT waivers and two ACT waivers. If you are an upcoming junior it is suggested that you take both the SAT and ACT once your junior year, however feel free to do what you are most comfortable with.

If you have any questions or concerns, please reach out to Mrs. Strickland.

The links to both testing sites are below:

ACT: https://www.act.org/content/act/en/register.html

post_text:
Back to School for Treutlen County Students:

The first day for traditional in-person school will be Monday, August 17th. For students opting to enroll in virtual school, the first day will be Wednesday, August 19th. (Reminder - please visit the school website and complete the enrollment application by the end of the day this Thursday, July 23rd.)

We have taken the safety of both staff and our students into consideration in the development of the back to school plan. Of course, as with every plan right now, this reopening plan is fluid and will change as necessary based on community circumstances and additional guidance from the state, DPH, CDC and other community considerations.

The school dress code will remain the same as last year, and school supply lists will be provided on July 27th. Information regarding Open House will be shared within the upcoming days.

We are looking forward to a different, but exciting year!

post_text:
A message from our Superintendent:

Dear Treutlen County Schools Families:

We know our families want to know exactly what school will look like in August, and we truly wish we could tell you. What we can tell you is not knowing is definitely not due to a lack of interest or planning. System staff and principals have worked diligently to come up with a variety of scenarios and options constructed around the most current information and guidelines. We are keenly aware that guidelines, restrictions, and expectations for public schools continue to change, and we want to be careful about giving information concerning the particulars about school opening so the message doesn‚Äôt change multiple times prior to August 5th. With that information, our goal is to be able to give you more detailed information on July 20th.

We hope you enjoy the rest of your summer.

Sincerely,
Bradley Anderson

Elisia Figueroa is the daughter of Chrel Duffie and Victor Figueroa.
She was a member of FCCLA for one year and FBLA for two years. She has been a THS Football cheerleader for three years and a THS Basketball cheerleader for two years.
She has been accepted into Valdosta State University where she plans to begin attending during the Summer 2020 semester and major in Business Management. In 10 years she sees herself owning a successful business, living a great life with her son and hopefully married.
Her favorite thing about high school is all the smart comments that she and Mr. Ricks trade back and forth to each other.
She would like to thank her mom for always pushing her to be the best that she can be.
Elisha's thoughts about the current pandemic and how it has affected her: "None of us saw this coming, and it‚Äôs sad that us seniors couldn‚Äôt finish out our senior year, nor have a prom, but this was out of our control and we all just have to have faith in God."

‚ÄúThank you all SO much for this amazing honor! It has been such a blessing to serve you all in some capacity the last four years. Four years ago, your freshman year, I walked into Treutlen High School as a brand new teacher ready to give back to the community that has given me so much. However, I did not realize how much you all would truly impact my life. You were patient with me as I worked to be the best that I could be for you all, and for that I am truly thankful. My little family and I are so blessed to be a part of Viking Nation, and we would not want to be anywhere else! Again, thank you and GO VIKINGS!‚Äù
Mrs. Strickland

Shamaree Anaria Ricks is the daughter of Christina Lovett & Jatavis Ricks.
Her favorite things about high school are spending time with her friends and talking to Mrs. Parrish. She enjoys eating and sleeping in her spare time.
She has been accepted to East Georgia State College and in 10 years, she sees herself graduated from college, getting a job in her field, getting married, having a family and being very financially stable.
She would like to thank Mrs. Parrish and some of her close family members because they believed in her more than she believed in herself.
Shamaree's thoughts about the current pandemic and how it has affected her: "This current pandemic has had a huge impact on my life. I didn‚Äôt get to say goodbye to some of my teachers that I strongly admire. Nor did I get to say goodbye to some of my classmates that I didn‚Äôt see outside of school on a daily basis. Last but not least, it also has shown me to pray even more."

TREUTLEN COUNTY LIBRARY INFO-PLEASE SHARE!
Due dates are temporarily suspended, and late books fees will not accrue through at least June 12th.

Karson Barry Walraven is the son of Jon and Tammi Walraven.
He is a member of the Treutlen County FFA and has served as sentinel, Vice President, and currently is President of the club. He was also in Math and Science Club for 3 years. He enjoys hanging out with his friends and family, and his favorite thing about high school is being able to see his friends everyday and being a part of FFA.
Karson is currently employed at Florida Hardware, and has been accepted to East Georgia State College. In ten years he sees himself with a degree in History and being able to have a job in Education.
He would like to thank all of his friends and family for helping him through high school. If it wasn‚Äôt for them, he wouldn‚Äôt be in the position that he is in today.
Karson's thoughts about the current pandemic and how it has affected him: "The current pandemic has had a major impact on my everyday life. I am no longer able to see my friends at school or live my everyday life like I would usually be able to."

Mrs. Tina and the Treutlen Chapter of Future Business Leaders of America would like to congratulate Kourtney Boswell, the first recipient of the THS FBLA/Red Cross Scholarship! Kourtney is shown here just before giving blood at the very first THS Blood Drive.
The amount of the scholarship, which is funded by the Red Cross, is determined by the number of blood donations received at our school blood drives. With the two successful drives we were able to hold, we received 73 donations. Due to Covid-19, the third blood drive had to be cancelled. This year‚Äôs scholarship is for $500.00. The application was judged based on an FBLA participation point scale and awarded to the THS graduating senior who had the most points.
Congratulations Kourtney, who served as our THS FBLA President for 2019-2020! We are so proud of you and know you will do great things! Also, a huge thank you to those of you who gave blood and made this scholarship possible!

post_text:
Upcoming juniors and seniors who have signed up for Work-Based Learning: please make sure you have secured a job no later than July 31st. As soon as you secure a job, please send a text to the the WBL coordinator, Mrs. Collins, stating your name and place of employment. Her phone number is 912-293-0303. If you did not sign up for WBL at advisement night or with Mrs. Strickland, you are not considered a WBL student.

Mrs. Collins will send you information on how to complete the paperwork. If you do not have a printer at home, you may pick up a copy of the paperwork from the front office. We will let you know when the paperwork is available.

If you do not have a job before July 31st, you will not be placed in the WBL program. If you have any questions or concerns, please send Mrs. Strickland an email.

We're still stuffing our buses with school lunches!

Next week beginning Monday, May 4, we will resume with bus route delivery to homes as we did when lunch deliveries first began. Each Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday for the next 3 weeks, the buses will leave at 10:00am as they did before, so delivery times should be close to the same as they were previously. Drive-thru pickup will also still be available on the TES side of the school from 11:00 -12:00 Monday -Wednesday.

We will continue practicing social distancing during drop-offs. Students please be ready to meet us at your house on Monday!

Naturi Newsome is the daughter of Tomeka Miller & James Newsome.
She has been a member of the Math & Science Club and FCCLA for three years and is a member of the THS Track team. She currently works at Cracker Barrel and after graduation, plans to join the Airforce and become a Diagnostic Imaging Tech. In 10 years she sees herself being rich, living the dream life and traveling around the world.
Naturi's favorite things about high school are chillin with the gang in Art class and arguing with Mr. Ricks & Mr. Salter. She also enjoys sleeping, shopping and watching Netflix.
She would like to thank her family and friends and also Mrs. Strickland for always being there, whether it was just talk or guide her in the right directions.
Naturi's thoughts about the current pandemic and how it's affected her: "This pandemic has ruined so many plans, but I know God has so much in store for me... so i will continue to pray & have faith that this will all be over soon."

Governor Kemp announced today that all Georgia schools would remain closed throughout the rest of the 2019-2020 school term. Online classes and distance learning will continue. School officials will discuss the many topics concerning the rest of the school year and will provide an update tomorrow, clarifying as many questions as possible at this time.
We are thankful to Viking Nation for your continued support and patience through this unprecedented situation.

"In light of everything going on and trying to find new ways of getting information out to students, we have created a Virtual Open House that students can attend via Zoom Meeting on the computer or smartphone app, or by calling in from their phone.

Governor Brian Kemp just signed Executive Order 3.16.20.01 closing all public elementary, secondary, and post-secondary public schools in Georgia from March 18, 2020 to March 31, 2020. He went on to ask Georgians to continue to follow best practices - ‚Äúwashing their hands regularly, isolating the elderly and chronically ill, and avoiding large events if possible - in the days and weeks ahead."

In accordance with this news, Treutlen County Schools will update their closure to extend through March 31st. All school-sponsored events, including prom, will be postponed until after this date as well.

We assure you that our students‚Äô and community‚Äôs safety is our top priority, and we encourage each of you to follow the governor‚Äôs recommendations. We will continue to follow the most current information and continue to assess schedules and procedures daily, posting regularly concerning these matters. Thank you for your cooperation and support.

post_text:
After much consideration, Treutlen County Schools will close for two weeks, from March 17 through March 27, for all students and staff. Any essential staff who needs to report will be notified by their supervisor. Our staff workday which was scheduled for tomorrow is also cancelled.

While we believe it is important to keep schools open for learning, we do not want to unnecessarily put our community at risk or create anxiety as our state and community face the uncertainty of the COVID-19 virus. We will make additional decisions as more information becomes available.

We encourage everyone to take this time to limit your interactions with others and do our part to prevent the potential spread of COVID-19. Please continue to check our Facebook page and website for updated information about school closings and resources.
